  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Domain Rating (DR)</strong> is a proprietary Ahrefs metric on a 0-to-100 logarithmic scale that measures the strength of a website's backlink profile. It counts referring domains, weights them by their own DR, and normalises the result. DR is <strong>not a Google ranking factor</strong>, but Ahrefs research shows a median DR 70+ site attracts roughly 10× more organic traffic than a DR 30 site.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Metric</div>
            <div class="tms-value"><span class="http-code-chip">DR 0–100</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Off-Page SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Traffic multiplier</div>
            <div class="tms-value">10× at DR 70+ vs DR 30</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every SEO tool has a domain-strength score, but DR is the one most link builders quote in outreach and the one most agencies show in reports. Knowing what it does and does not measure is the difference between spending link-building budget well and wasting it.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a domain rating?</h2>
        <p>Domain Rating is Ahrefs' single-number summary of a domain's backlink profile. It is calculated from three inputs: the number of unique referring domains, the DR of each referring domain, and how many other sites those domains also link to. The math is recursive — similar in spirit to Google's original PageRank paper.</p>
        <p>The 0-100 scale is logarithmic. Moving from DR 20 to DR 30 might take a handful of good links. Moving from DR 70 to DR 80 requires years of high-authority coverage. Ahrefs updates DR near real-time as new links are discovered by its crawler.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance</div>
          <p>Google does not use DR. However, the underlying signal DR measures — the referring-domain graph — is one of the strongest actual ranking factors Google uses. DR is a useful proxy; it is not the signal itself.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Domain Rating matters</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Traffic correlation.</strong> Ahrefs' industry study found DR 70+ sites attract roughly 10× more organic traffic than DR 30 sites.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive analysis.</strong> Benchmark against the top 5 URLs for your target keyword. If they average DR 75 and you sit at DR 25, prioritise long-tail queries first.</li>
          <li><strong>Link outreach filtering.</strong> Filter guest-post and partnership targets by DR to concentrate effort on sites that actually move the needle.</li>
          <li><strong>Progress reporting.</strong> DR is a stable, monthly-updating KPI that clients understand. It shows link-building ROI even before rankings catch up.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Domain Rating works</h2>
        <p>Ahrefs recalculates DR every few days as its crawler discovers new links. Three inputs feed the score:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Referring domains.</strong> The count of unique root domains linking to your site.</li>
          <li><strong>Referring-domain DR.</strong> A link from DR 80 counts more than 50 links from DR 10 sites.</li>
          <li><strong>Link dilution.</strong> If a linking domain also links to thousands of other sites, each individual link carries less weight.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>The output is normalised to a 0-100 logarithmic scale.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Domain Rating: types and variants</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Impact</th><th>Use case</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>DR 0-19</strong></td><td>New or thin domain</td><td>Weak profile</td><td>Focus on foundational links</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>DR 20-39</strong></td><td>Competitive locally</td><td>Emerging authority</td><td>Local citations + niche guest posts</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>DR 40-59</strong></td><td>Strong SMB range</td><td>Rankable in most niches</td><td>Digital PR + resource pages</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>DR 60-79</strong></td><td>Category leader</td><td>Enterprise territory</td><td>Original research + syndication</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>DR 80-100</strong></td><td>Major brand or publisher</td><td>Household name</td><td>Reputation management</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Domain Rating examples</h2>
        <p>Two real client scenarios show how DR gets used in practice.</p>

        <h3>1. SaaS startup competitive check</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Target keyword: "project management software"</span><br>
          Position 1: DR <span class="uf-status">85</span><br>
          Position 2: DR <span class="uf-status">78</span><br>
          Position 3: DR <span class="uf-status">72</span><br>
          Your site: DR <span class="uf-old">15</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Signal: pursue long-tail before head terms</span>
        </div>

        <h3>2. Dental practice link-building ROI</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          Month 0 DR: <span class="uf-old">12</span><span class="uf-arrow">→</span>Month 6 DR: <span class="uf-new">28</span><br>
          Organic traffic growth: <span class="uf-new">+340%</span><br>
          Referring domains gained: <span class="uf-new">63</span>
        </div>

        <h3>3. Content-hub link acquisition</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># B2B research study earned 47 links in 3 months</span><br>
          DR change: <span class="uf-old">31</span><span class="uf-arrow">→</span><span class="uf-new">44</span><br>
          Cost per link: <span class="uf-status">$180</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Domain Rating vs Domain Authority</h2>
        <p>DR and DA measure the same underlying signal — the backlink graph — but with different methodology and update cadence.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use DR (Ahrefs) when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You work in Ahrefs as your primary SEO stack</li>
              <li>You want near-real-time updates as new links appear</li>
              <li>You are running large-scale link audits</li>
              <li>You need to compare against Ahrefs-benchmarked competitors</li>
              <li>Your team standardises on Ahrefs UGC</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use DA (Moz) when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You already work in Moz Pro or Link Explorer</li>
              <li>You want a metric that includes spam-score signals</li>
              <li>You are evaluating overall domain quality, not link volume alone</li>
              <li>Your client reports historically show DA</li>
              <li>You are prospecting with editorial-vetting criteria</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for Domain Rating</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Prioritise high-DR referring domains.</strong> One DR 70 link from a news site outweighs 50 DR 10 blog links.</li>
          <li><strong>Build consistently.</strong> Suspicious velocity spikes get filtered by both Ahrefs and Google.</li>
          <li><strong>Diversify referring domains.</strong> 10 links from 10 sites beats 100 links from 1 site.</li>
          <li><strong>Use DR for benchmarks, not KPIs.</strong> Compare against SERP competitors, not universal targets.</li>
          <li><strong>Track DR alongside referring domains.</strong> Referring-domain count is the more actionable operational metric.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignore DR for individual pages.</strong> DR is domain-level; use URL Rating (UR) for page-level analysis.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit toxic links quarterly.</strong> Disavow spam domains before they distort your DR calculation.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — chasing DR instead of relevance</div>
          <p>A DR 80 link from an unrelated site can be worth less than a DR 40 link from a topically relevant site. Relevance beats raw authority every time in modern Google. Filter outreach by topical fit first, DR second.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Domain Rating mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Treating DR as a ranking factor.</strong> It is not. It is a proxy for one.</li>
          <li><strong>Chasing arbitrary DR targets.</strong> Benchmark against competitors, not round numbers.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritising quantity over quality.</strong> 100 low-DR links move DR less than 5 high-DR links.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring page-level authority.</strong> High DR does not guarantee any individual URL ranks — use UR.</li>
          <li><strong>Buying DR-inflating links.</strong> Ahrefs' disavow-net-of-toxic filters catch it; Google follows.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
